GraphTNI: A Theoretical Framework for Error-Controlled Transformer-Augmented Approximation of N-Body Gravitational Systems

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Affiliation: Independent Researcher
Date: April 2026

---

Abstract

We establish a rigorous mathematical foundation for using transformer-based sequence models as surrogate integrators for the gravitational N-body problem. We define the Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI), a permutation-equivariant architecture that directly approximates the Hamiltonian flow map $\Phi_h$ over a timestep $h$. The core contribution is a global error bound for a hybrid predictor-corrector scheme (Theorem 2), proving that periodic synchronization with a symplectic reference solver every $C$ steps transforms exponential error growth from the base timestep $h$ into growth governed by the correction interval $C h$. We further prove that training on symplectic data induces a shadow Hamiltonian $\tilde{\mathcal{H}}_\theta$, guaranteeing $\mathcal{O}(t)$ energy drift (Proposition 1). To ground the assumed local error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$, we provide an approximation rate (Theorem 5) showing that for Hölder-smooth flows, a transformer of width $d_{\text{model}}$ and depth $L$ achieves $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}} = \mathcal{O}(d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D} + L^{-s/D})$, where $D = 6N$ is the phase-space dimension. We derive conditions under which sparse attention achieves $\mathcal{O}(N)$ complexity for fixed absolute error (Theorem 4, Corollary 4). Finally, we position this work within the 2024–2026 SciML landscape, showing that Theorem 2 provides the missing theoretical justification for recent empirical successes in adaptive-timestep reinforcement learning and hybrid physical-neural ODEs. This framework establishes explicit, falsifiable criteria for the error-controlled deployment of transformer-based surrogates in chaotic Hamiltonian systems.

