1. Introduction

The gravitational N-body problem—predicting the motion of $N$ point masses under mutual Newtonian attraction—is a cornerstone of computational astrophysics, orbital mechanics, and dynamical systems theory. Its governing equations form a system of $6N$ coupled, nonlinear ordinary differential equations (ODEs) that admit no general closed-form solution for $N \ge 3$. Numerical integration is therefore unavoidable, but classical integrators face a fundamental tension: high-order accuracy demands small timesteps, while long-timescale simulations (e.g., galaxy evolution, satellite constellation stability) require millions of steps, making the computational cost prohibitive.

Recent advances in Scientific Machine Learning (SciML) have explored neural surrogates to accelerate these simulations. Approaches range from learning the vector field (Neural ODEs, Hamiltonian Neural Networks) to learning the flow map directly (neural operators, transformers). However, the theoretical understanding of when and why such surrogates succeed—particularly in chaotic regimes—has lagged far behind empirical demonstrations. Critical questions remain unanswered: How does the local approximation error of a learned model compound over time? Can a non-symplectic model preserve long-term energy stability? What is the optimal frequency for correcting the surrogate with a trusted solver?

This dissertation addresses these questions through a purely theoretical framework. We make no empirical claims and report no simulation data; our contributions are strictly mathematical and architectural. The work is structured as follows:

· Section 2 reviews Hamiltonian dynamics and numerical error analysis.
· Section 3 positions the proposed GraphTNI within the 2024–2026 SciML landscape, including recent hybrid physical-neural ODEs and adaptive-timestep reinforcement learning methods.
· Section 4 defines the Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI), a permutation-equivariant architecture for flow map approximation.
· Section 5 provides theoretical approximation guarantees, bounding the local error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ using transformer universal approximation theory.
· Section 6 presents the hybrid predictor-corrector algorithm and proves the central global error bound (Theorem 2), along with an analysis of the optimal correction interval $C_{\text{opt}}$.
· Section 7 demonstrates that training on symplectic data endows GraphTNI with a shadow Hamiltonian, yielding $\mathcal{O}(t)$ energy drift.
· Section 8 analyzes computational complexity, proving that sparse attention can reduce the cost to $\mathcal{O}(N)$ for fixed absolute error.
· Section 9 discusses limitations, failure modes, and directions for future work.
· Section 10 concludes.

1.1 Scope and Limitations
This document contains no experimental results, performance benchmarks, or simulation data. It is a work of theoretical computer science and applied mathematics. All claims are either proven theorems or formal conjectures with stated assumptions.

1.2 Notation

· $\mathcal{M} \subset \mathbb{R}^{6N}$: phase space.
· $\mathbf{x}(t) = (\mathbf{q}(t), \mathbf{p}(t)) \in \mathcal{M}$: state vector, with positions $\mathbf{q} \in \mathbb{R}^{3N}$ and momenta $\mathbf{p} \in \mathbb{R}^{3N}$.
· $\Phi_h: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{M}$: exact flow map over timestep $h > 0$.
· $J = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & I \\ -I & 0 \end{pmatrix}$: standard symplectic matrix.
· $L$: Lipschitz constant of the vector field $f(\mathbf{x}) = J \nabla \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x})$.
· $\lambda_{\max}$: maximal Lyapunov exponent; $t_\lambda = 1/\lambda_{\max}$ is the Lyapunov time.

