2. Mathematical Preliminaries

2.1 Hamiltonian Dynamics of the N-Body Problem
The Hamiltonian for $N$ gravitating point masses $m_i$ is
\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{q}, \mathbf{p}) = \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{\|\mathbf{p}_i\|^2}{2m_i} - \sum_{1 \le i < j \le N} \frac{G m_i m_j}{\|\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j\|}. \tag{1} 


Hamilton's equations read $\dot{\mathbf{x}} = J \nabla_{\mathbf{x}} \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x})$. The flow $\Phi_h$ is a symplectic transformation, preserving the canonical two-form $\omega = d\mathbf{q} \wedge d\mathbf{p}$, for all points where the potential is non-singular.

2.2 Numerical Integration and Error Accumulation
Let $\Psi_h$ be a one-step numerical integrator approximating $\Phi_h$. The local truncation error is $\tau(\mathbf{x}, h) = \Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \Psi_h(\mathbf{x})$.

Theorem 1 (Global Error for Lipschitz Flows). Assume the vector field $f(\mathbf{x})$ is Lipschitz continuous with constant $L$. For a method of order $p$ (i.e., $\|\tau\| = \mathcal{O}(h^{p+1})$), the global error after $M$ steps satisfies
\|\mathbf{x}_M - \Phi_{Mh}(\mathbf{x}_0)\| \le C h^p \frac{e^{L M h} - 1}{L}. \tag{2} 


Proof. Standard result in numerical ODE theory (Hairer, Lubich, & Wanner, 2006). ∎

The exponential factor $e^{L M h}$ highlights the difficulty of long-time integration in chaotic systems, where $L \approx \lambda_{\max}$.

2.3 Chaos and Lyapunov Time
The maximal Lyapunov exponent is defined as
\lambda_{\max} = \lim_{t \to \infty} \lim_{\delta \mathbf{x}_0 \to 0} \frac{1}{t} \ln \frac{\|\delta \mathbf{x}(t)\|}{\|\delta \mathbf{x}_0\|}. \tag{3} 


The Lyapunov time $t_\lambda = 1/\lambda_{\max}$ is the characteristic e-folding time for phase-space errors. Even for $N=3$, $t_\lambda$ can be on the order of a few orbital periods, making long-term prediction exponentially sensitive to initial conditions.

