3.1 Why Autoregressive Flow Maps?
HNNs and Neural ODEs learn the vector field and thus require an ODE solver at inference time, incurring multiple function evaluations per effective timestep. In contrast, GraphTNI directly approximates the flow map $\Phi_h$, requiring only a single forward pass per timestep. This shifts computational cost from integration to inference.

3.2 Relation to Hybrid Physical-Neural ODEs
Zhong et al. (2022) proposed a Particle-Mesh (PM) solver augmented with a neural network that corrects the residual force on small scales. Their method achieves $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$ scaling but lacks rigorous error control. Our Theorem 2 provides a framework for analyzing such hybrid schemes: the PM solver can be viewed as a fast surrogate $\Psi_h$, and periodic full $N$-body corrections play the role of $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$. Our bound quantifies the trade-off between correction frequency and accuracy.

3.3 Relation to Adaptive Timestep RL
Saz Ulibarrena (Leiden PhD, 2025) and concurrent work (Feb 2025) use reinforcement learning to adapt the timestep $h$ of a symplectic integrator based on local dynamics, achieving speedups while maintaining energy conservation. Theorem 2 provides the missing theoretical justification for why this works: by reducing $h$ in regions of high curvature (large $L$), the method effectively keeps the local error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ constant, which our bound shows is sufficient to control global error. We conjecture that the optimal policy should approximately satisfy $h(\mathbf{x}) \propto 1/L(\mathbf{x})$, aligning with Eq. (12) for fixed $C$.

3.4 Universal Approximation of Flow Maps
Transformers are universal approximators of sequence-to-sequence functions (Yun et al., 2019) and of integral operators between Hölder spaces (Lu et al., 2021; Kovachki et al., 2023). Since $\Phi_h$ is a composition of continuous maps, these results guarantee that a sufficiently large transformer can approximate $\Phi_h$ to arbitrary precision on compact subsets of $\mathcal{M}$. We quantify this in Section 5.

