4. Graph Transformer Neural Integrator (GraphTNI) Architecture

We now define the GraphTNI, a permutation-equivariant transformer designed to approximate the flow map $\Phi_h$.

4.1 Motivation for Equivariance
The N-body system is invariant under permutation of particle labels. Standard transformers break this invariance due to positional encodings. We enforce permutation equivariance by using a graph-based tokenization and a Deep Sets readout.

Definition 1 (Equivariant Token Embedding). For the $i$-th particle, the initial token embedding is computed from its own state and the relative states of all other particles:
\mathbf{e}_i^{(0)} = \phi_{\text{node}}(\mathbf{q}_i, \mathbf{p}_i) + \sum_{j \neq i} \psi_{\text{edge}}(\mathbf{q}_i - \mathbf{q}_j, \mathbf{p}_i - \mathbf{p}_j), \tag{4} 


where $\phi_{\text{node}}: \mathbb{R}^6 \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ and $\psi_{\text{edge}}: \mathbb{R}^6 \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ are learnable multi-layer perceptrons (MLPs).

Definition 2 (Autoregressive Flow Approximation). Given a context window of $K$ consecutive states $X_t = (\mathbf{x}_{t-K+1}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_t)$, the GraphTNI predicts the state at $t+1$:
\hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t+1} = \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t-K+1}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_t). \tag{5} 

Definition 3 (Transformer Block). The token embeddings are processed by $L$ decoder layers, each applying causal multi-head self-attention followed by a position-wise feed-forward network (FFN). Causal masking ensures that predictions depend only on past states. The output of the final layer is a sequence of token embeddings $\mathbf{h}_i^{(L)} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ for $i = 1, \dots, N$.

Definition 4 (Equivariant Readout). To predict the state increment for particle $i$, we use a permutation-invariant aggregation of all token embeddings:
\Delta \hat{\mathbf{x}}_i = \rho\!\left( \mathbf{h}_i^{(L)}, \sum_{j \neq i} \gamma(\mathbf{h}_i^{(L)}, \mathbf{h}_j^{(L)}) \right), \tag{6} 


where $\rho: \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}} \times d_{\text{model}}} \to \mathbb{R}^6$ and $\gamma: \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}} \times d_{\text{model}}} \to \mathbb{R}^{d_{\text{model}}}$ are MLPs. The final predicted state is
\hat{\mathbf{x}}_{t+1, i} = \mathbf{x}_{t,i} + \Delta \hat{\mathbf{x}}_i. \tag{7} 


The residual formulation encourages learning of small increments.

4.2 Context Window $K$ and Memory of the Flow
The exact flow $\Phi_h$ is a Markovian map: $\mathbf{x}_{t+1}$ depends only on $\mathbf{x}_t$. However, the GraphTNI uses a context window of length $K$ to capture higher-order dynamics implicitly learned from discrete data. We analyze the role of $K$ in Section 5.2.

