5. Theoretical Approximation Guarantees for $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$

The hybrid error bound in Section 6 assumes a uniform local error bound $\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$. We now provide theoretical justification for this assumption.

5.1 Approximation Rate for Hölder-Smooth Flows

Theorem 5 (Approximation Rate for GraphTNI). Suppose the flow map $\Phi_h$ is $s$-Hölder smooth on a compact subset $\mathcal{K} \subset \mathcal{M}$, with $s > 0$. Then there exists a GraphTNI architecture with depth $L$ and width $d_{\text{model}}$ such that
\sup_{\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{K}} \|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le C_1 d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D} + C_2 L^{-s/D}, \tag{8} 


where $D = 6N$ is the phase-space dimension, and $C_1, C_2$ are constants depending on the smoothness norm and architecture details.

Proof Sketch. This result synthesizes two lines of work. First, the universal approximation theorem for transformers on sequence-to-sequence functions (Yun et al., 2019) guarantees that a transformer can approximate any continuous function on a compact domain to arbitrary precision. Second, recent results on the approximation rates of neural operators (Lu et al., 2021; Kovachki et al., 2023) provide quantitative bounds for learning mappings between function spaces. The Hölder smoothness of $\Phi_h$ follows from the smoothness of the Hamiltonian vector field away from collisions. The rate $d_{\text{model}}^{-s/D}$ is standard for neural network approximation of smooth functions on $D$-dimensional domains; the depth-dependent term $L^{-s/D}$ reflects the compositional structure of the transformer. The permutation-equivariant architecture does not degrade the rate, as the Deep Sets aggregation preserves the smoothness class. ∎

Corollary 3 (Data Requirements). To achieve a target local error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$, the number of training samples $|\mathcal{D}_{\text{train}}|$ must scale as $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}^{-D/s})$ in the worst case, due to the curse of dimensionality. This highlights the need for dimensionality reduction techniques (e.g., sparse attention, graph neural networks) to make training feasible for large $N$.

5.2 The Role of Context Window $K$

Lemma 1 (Memory of Discrete Flow). Let the training data be generated by a symplectic integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{symp}}$ of order $p$. Then the exact discrete flow $\Phi_h^{\text{symp}}$ has a Markov property: $\mathbf{x}_{t+1}$ depends only on $\mathbf{x}_t$. However, the error between $\Phi_h^{\text{symp}}$ and the true flow $\Phi_h$ depends on derivatives up to order $p+1$, which are not directly observable from a single state. A context window of length $K \ge p+1$ allows the transformer to implicitly estimate these higher-order derivatives, reducing the irreducible approximation error.

Conjecture 1 (Optimal Context Length). For a symplectic integrator of order $p$, the minimal context window required to achieve approximation error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ is $K = p+1$. Larger $K$ may improve robustness to noise but does not reduce the asymptotic error rate.

Justification. The local truncation error of a $p$-th order method is $\mathcal{O}(h^{p+1})$ and depends on the $(p+1)$-st derivative of the vector field. A sequence of $p+1$ consecutive states provides sufficient information to estimate these derivatives via finite differences. ∎

5.3 Probabilistic Generalization Bound
Theorem 5 provides a uniform bound over $\mathcal{K}$. In practice, the error is state-dependent. We conjecture a probabilistic bound:

Conjecture 2 (Probabilistic Error Bound). For states drawn from the invariant measure of the system, the local error satisfies $\mathbb{P}(\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| > \epsilon) \le \delta$, where $\delta$ decays exponentially with training set size. This implies that rare, high-error states (e.g., close encounters) may require special handling (see Section 9).

