6. The Hybrid Predictor-Corrector Framework

Direct autoregressive rollout of GraphTNI suffers from compounding error. We mitigate this by periodically synchronizing with a trusted reference integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$.

6.1 Algorithm Definition

Algorithm 1: Hybrid GraphTNI-Augmented Evolution
Input: Initial state $\mathbf{x}_0$, context length $K$, correction interval $C \in \mathbb{N}^+$.
Output: Sequence of states $\mathbf{x}_t$ for $t = 0, 1, \dots$
1: $t \leftarrow 0$
2: while $t < T_{\text{max}}$ do
3: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; for $j = 1$ to $C$ do
4: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $\mathbf{x}_{t+j} \leftarrow \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_{t+j-K}, \dots, \mathbf{x}_{t+j-1})$
5: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; end for
6: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $\mathbf{x}_{t+C} \leftarrow \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\mathbf{x}_{t+C-1})$
7: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; $t \leftarrow t + C$
8: end while

Remark 1 (Geometric Interpretation). Algorithm 1 can be viewed as a composition method. After the first correction at step $C$, the state is advanced by $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}} \circ \text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}$. After $M$ cycles, the overall map is
\Psi_{M C h} = \underbrace{\Phi_h^{\text{ref}} \circ \text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1} \circ \cdots \circ \Phi_h^{\text{ref}} \circ \text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}}_{M \text{ cycles}}. 


Unlike standard composition methods (e.g., Yoshida splitting) which require all components to be symplectic, Theorem 2 shows global error is controlled even when $\text{GraphTNI}_\theta$ is not symplectic, provided $C$ satisfies Eq. (12). This generalizes symplectic splitting to non-symplectic surrogates.

6.2 Global Error Bound

Theorem 2 (Global Error Bound for Hybrid Correction).
Let GraphTNI satisfy a local error bound $\|\Phi_h(\mathbf{x}) - \text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x})\| \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ for all $\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{K}$. Let the reference integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{ref}}$ have local error $\epsilon_{\text{ref}}$. Assume the vector field has Lipschitz constant $L$. Then the global error after $M$ correction cycles (i.e., $T = M C h$) satisfies
\|\mathbf{x}_{M \cdot C} - \Phi_{M C h}(\mathbf{x}_0)\| \le \left( \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \frac{e^{L C h} - 1}{e^{L h} - 1} \right) \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1} + \mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{ref}}). \tag{9} 

Proof.
Define the error after a single block of $C$ GraphTNI steps starting from an exact state $\mathbf{y}$:
E_C(\mathbf{y}) = \|\text{GraphTNI}_\theta^C(\mathbf{y}) - \Phi_{C h}(\mathbf{y})\|. 


Using the Lipschitz property and the local error bound, we propagate the error stepwise:
E_1 \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}, \quad E_2 \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} + E_1 e^{L h}, \quad \dots 


By induction,
E_C \le \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \sum_{k=0}^{C-1} e^{L k h} = \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} \frac{e^{L C h} - 1}{e^{L h} - 1}. \tag{10} 


Now apply the reference correction. The state after correction is $\mathbf{x}_C^{\text{corr}} = \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}(\mathbf{y}))$. The error after correction is bounded by
E_{\text{reset}} \le \| \Phi_h(\text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}(\mathbf{y})) - \Phi_h^{\text{ref}}(\text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}(\mathbf{y})) \| + \| \Phi_h(\text{GraphTNI}_\theta^{C-1}(\mathbf{y})) - \Phi_h(\Phi_{(C-1)h}(\mathbf{y})) \|. 


The first term is $\le \epsilon_{\text{ref}}$. The second term is $\le e^{L h} E_{C-1}$. Thus
E_{\text{reset}} \le \epsilon_{\text{ref}} + e^{L h} E_C. \tag{11} 


Treating each correction cycle as a macro-step with error per cycle $E_{\text{reset}}$, the error after $M$ cycles is
E_{M \cdot C} \le E_{\text{reset}} \sum_{k=0}^{M-1} e^{k L C h} = E_{\text{reset}} \frac{e^{L M C h} - 1}{e^{L C h} - 1}. 


Substituting the bound for $E_{\text{reset}}$ from (11) and the expression for $E_C$ from (10) yields (9), where the $\mathcal{O}(\epsilon_{\text{ref}})$ term absorbs the additive $\epsilon_{\text{ref}}$. ∎

Corollary 1 (Error Reset Property). The global error grows exponentially at a rate dictated by the correction interval $C h$, not the base timestep $h$. The error doubling time is $t_{\text{double}} = (\ln 2) / (L C h)$, which is $C$ times larger than that of pure GraphTNI rollout.

6.3 Optimal and Adaptive Correction Interval
From Eq. (10), the error per cycle $E_C$ grows with $C$. Balancing computational cost (larger $C$ reduces expensive reference evaluations) against accuracy yields a theoretical optimum for fixed $L$:
C_{\text{opt}} = \left\lfloor \frac{1}{L h} \ln\!\left( \frac{\epsilon_{\text{ref}}}{\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}} (e^{L h} - 1) + 1 \right) \right\rfloor. \tag{12} 

Physical Interpretation. If we approximate $L \approx \lambda_{\max}$ and set $C h = 0.1 \, t_\lambda$, then $E_C \approx \epsilon_{\text{LLM}} e^{0.1} \approx 1.1 \epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$. Synchronizing every 10% of the Lyapunov time keeps the local error nearly constant, preventing exponential blow-up.

Remark 2 (Adaptive Correction). In realistic N-body systems, $L$ varies dramatically—soaring during close encounters and falling in quiescent regions. A fixed $C$ is therefore suboptimal. A natural extension is to make $C$ state-dependent: $C = C(\mathbf{x})$. Recent work (Saz Ulibarrena, 2025) uses reinforcement learning to adapt the timestep $h$. Our framework suggests that the optimal policy should approximately satisfy $C(\mathbf{x}) \cdot h \propto 1/L(\mathbf{x})$. Future work could combine RL with our error bound to learn $C(\mathbf{x})$ directly.

