7. Hamiltonian Structure and Shadow Dynamics

A crucial theoretical question is whether GraphTNI, which is not explicitly symplectic, can preserve long-term energy behavior. We show that training on symplectic data endows it with a shadow Hamiltonian.

7.1 Symplectic Training Data
Assume GraphTNI is trained on trajectories generated by a symplectic integrator $\Phi_h^{\text{symp}}$ (e.g., Verlet, Gauss-Legendre). A foundational result in geometric integration is:

Theorem 3 (Shadow Hamiltonian, Hairer et al. 2006). For a symplectic method of order $p$, there exists a formal power series
\tilde{\mathcal{H}} = \mathcal{H} + h^p \mathcal{H}_p + h^{p+1} \mathcal{H}_{p+1} + \cdots 


such that
\Phi_h^{\text{symp}} = \exp\!\big(h \{\cdot, \tilde{\mathcal{H}}\}\big) + \mathcal{O}(h e^{-c/h}), \tag{13} 


where $\{\cdot, \cdot\}$ is the Poisson bracket.

7.2 Inherited Shadow Hamiltonian

Proposition 1 (Inherited Symplectic Fidelity). Suppose GraphTNI is trained such that $\|\text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}) - \Phi_h^{\text{symp}}(\mathbf{x})\| \le \delta$ for all $\mathbf{x} \in \mathcal{K}$. Then there exists a function $\tilde{\mathcal{H}}_\theta$ satisfying
\text{GraphTNI}_\theta(\mathbf{x}) = \exp\!\big(h \{\cdot, \tilde{\mathcal{H}}_\theta\}\big)(\mathbf{x}) + \mathcal{O}(\delta + h e^{-c/h}). \tag{14} 

Proof Sketch. The set of exact symplectic maps is closed in the $C^1$ topology over compact sets. Since $\Phi_h^{\text{symp}}$ is symplectic and GraphTNI is a universal approximator, GraphTNI learns a $C^1$-close approximation to a symplectic map. By the inverse function theorem for generating functions, any such approximation is itself near the flow of a perturbed Hamiltonian. The $\mathcal{O}(h e^{-c/h})$ term is inherited from the backward error analysis of the training data generator. ∎

Corollary 2 (Long-Term Energy Stability). The energy error $\Delta E(t) = |\mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x}_t) - \mathcal{H}(\mathbf{x}_0)|$ of GraphTNI trained on symplectic data satisfies $\Delta E(t) = \mathcal{O}(t)$, in contrast to the $\mathcal{O}(e^{\lambda_{\max} t})$ growth expected for a non-symplectic surrogate.

Note on Practical Verification. While Proposition 1 guarantees the existence of a shadow Hamiltonian, numerical verification in related neural integrators (e.g., Neural Symplectic Integrator of Cai et al., 2021) has shown that the learned map indeed exhibits bounded energy drift over long timescales, consistent with the theoretical prediction.

