8. Complexity Analysis and Sparse Attention

A common criticism of transformers is the $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ complexity of dense self-attention. We now prove that sparse attention preserves approximation fidelity while reducing complexity.

8.1 Force Decay and Locality
In gravitational systems, the pairwise force decays as $r_{ij}^{-2}$. For a softened potential, the interaction strength is bounded.

Definition 5 (Sparse Attention Mask). For each query particle $i$, restrict attention to the set $\mathcal{N}_i$ of $k$ nearest neighbors in position space. The sparse attention operation is
\text{SparseAttn}(\mathbf{Q}, \mathbf{K}, \mathbf{V})_i = \sum_{j \in \mathcal{N}_i} \text{softmax}\!\left(\frac{\mathbf{Q}_i \mathbf{K}_j^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right) \mathbf{V}_j. \tag{15} 

Theorem 4 (Sparse Attention Approximation Error). Suppose the interaction kernel $F(r) \sim r^{-\alpha}$ with $\alpha > 3$. Then the error introduced by restricting attention to $k$ nearest neighbors is bounded by
\|\text{DenseAttn} - \text{SparseAttn}\| \le C k^{-\alpha/3} N, \tag{16} 


while the computational complexity reduces from $\mathcal{O}(N^2)$ to $\mathcal{O}(N k)$.

Proof Sketch. The error from neglecting distant particles is bounded by the sum of forces beyond the $k$-th neighbor. Using the decay law and an integral approximation over the particle distribution, one obtains the stated bound. The complexity follows directly from the definition. ∎

Corollary 4 (Gravity Case). For the gravitational potential ($\alpha = 2$), Eq. (16) gives error $\sim k^{-2/3} N$. To achieve an absolute error $\epsilon$, we require $k = \lceil (C/\epsilon)^{3/2} \rceil$. For a fixed absolute tolerance $\epsilon$ (e.g., $10^{-3}$), $k$ is independent of $N$, yielding $\mathcal{O}(N)$ complexity—matching the scaling of Fast Multipole Methods.

Corollary 5 (Tree-Based Sparse Attention). If the nearest-neighbor sets $\mathcal{N}_i$ are constructed using a Barnes-Hut octree with opening angle $\theta$, then $k = \mathcal{O}(\log N)$ and the total complexity becomes $\mathcal{O}(N \log N)$, matching state-of-the-art tree codes.

8.2 Impact on Theorem 2
Theorem 2's proof relies only on the Lipschitz constant $L$ of the effective vector field, not on the specific attention mechanism. Therefore, the global error bound holds unchanged for the sparse-attention variant, provided the local error $\epsilon_{\text{LLM}}$ is measured under the sparse architecture.

